definition.value: A gender role is a social role encompassing a range of behaviors and attitudes that are generally considered culturally and/or socially acceptable, appropriate, or desirable for people based on their actual or perceived gender, sex and/or sexuality.
Previous IRI was http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GSSO_000087.
Male-associated gender-specific social roles and behaviors unrelated to biologic function.
Previous IRI was http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GSSO_000091.
Female-associated gender-specific social roles and behaviors unrelated to biologic function.
Previous IRI was http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GSSO_000092.
A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's occurrence.
An organismal quality inhering in a bearer or a population by virtue of the bearer's disposition to survive and develop normally or the number of surviving individuals in a given population.
A reproductive quality inhering in an organism or population by virtue of the bearer's potential reproductive capacity and measured by the number of gametes.
A fertility quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being capable of initiating, sustaining, or supporting reproduction.
A fertility quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being incapable of initiating, sustaining, or supporting reproduction.
A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's successive change from one thing or state to another and back again.
A quality which inheres in an process.
A mating type that indicates whether the F plasmid has integrated into the chromosome.
A mating type which occurs in yeast.
A monadic quality of continuant that exists at the cellular level of organization.
A measure of the frequency of occurrence of a specific illness in a defined population during a specified interval.
A quality inhering in a population by virtue of the proportion of its members that are ill at a given time.
The proportion of patients with a particular disease during a given year per given unit of population.
A viability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's condition before death.
A viability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the cessation of the bearer's life.
An organismal quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ability to produce new life or offspring.
An organismal quality occurring in an individual or a population that undergoes sexual reproduction, somewhat analogous to the concept of "sexes" in multicellular sexual organisms.
A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to being capable of indefinite growth or division.
An organismal quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's consisting cells.
A cellularity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's consisting of more than one cell.
A cellularity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's consisting of exactly one cell.
A quality that inheres in an entire organism or part of an organism.
Qualities and characterization of various types of populations within a social or geographic group, with emphasis on demography, health status, and socioeconomic factors.
A physical quality which inheres in an process.
Handedness where the organism preferentially uses the left hand or foot for tasks requiring the use of a single hand or foot or a dominant hand or foot.
Handedness where the organism preferentially uses the right hand or foot for tasks requiring the use of a single hand or foot or a dominant hand or foot.
Handedness where the organism exhibits no overall dominance in the use of right or left hand or foot in the performance of tasks that require one hand or foot or a dominant hand or foot.
A temporal distribution pattern of process occurrences within a regulation/reference process.
A group of independent but interrelated elements comprising a unified whole.
A material entity consisting of multiple components that are causally integrated.
An occurrent that exists in time by occurring or happening, has temporal parts and always involves and depends on some entity.
A follicle that has reached the most mature stage of folliculogenesis, characterized by the presence of the antrum.
Material anatomical entity that is a single connected structure with inherent 3D shape generated by coordinated expression of the organism's own genome.
A multicellular structure that is a part of an organ.
An entire span of an organism's life, commencing with the zygote stage and ending in the death of the organism.

An integrative interaction network process of an organism that starts from the moment when the first cell forms, has its blueprint stored in the genotype, and performs its dynamic process by interacting with its environment to achieve its survival and other motivations.
Common chamber into which the intestines and excretory system opens. Arises during development in all vertebrates, but in many it becomes subdivided, lost or incorporated into other structures.

A portion of organism substance that is the product of an excretion process that will be eliminated from the body. An excretion process is elimination by an organism of the waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity.
A fluid that is composed of blood plasma and erythrocytes.
Circulating fluid that is part of the hemolymphoid system. Blood, lymph, interstitial fluid or its analogs.
Dense regular connective tissue connecting two or more adjacent skeletal elements or supporting an organ.
A portion of organism substance that is produced by exocrine glands.

Material anatomical entity in a gaseous, liquid, semisolid or solid state; produced by anatomical structures or derived from inhaled and ingested substances that have been modified by anatomical structures as they pass through the body.
Anatomical group that is has as its parts distinct anatomical structures interconnected by anatomical structures at a lower level of granularity.
A gonad that produces and releases sperm.
The testes present as internal and external in different species. For example, the testes are external in humans and internal in elephants.
Collective designation for those tissues capable of secreting hormones.

The system of glands that release their secretions (hormones) directly into the circulatory system. In addition to the endocrine glands, included are the chromaffin system and the neurosecretory systems.
A intromittent organ in certain biologically male organisms. In placental mammals, this also serves as the organ of urination.
Sometimes transgender people refer to their clitoris as a penis in order to reduce dysphoria associated with it.
The organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.
The external and internal organs involved in the functions of reproduction.
Reproductive organ that produces and releases eggs (ovary) or sperm (testis).
A gonad that produces and releases ova.
A tube or collection of tubes in an animal from the ovaries to the outside of the body.
